WEBVTT

00:06.267 --> 00:06.484
.

00:06.528 --> 00:10.053
- Look, I know we haven't
talked in a while, but...

00:10.097 --> 00:13.578
I have to tell you this, and...

00:13.622 --> 00:16.059
I don't know,
you might not like it.

00:18.714 --> 00:21.717
What do you get when you...

00:21.760 --> 00:24.459
cross an elephant

00:24.502 --> 00:26.548
with a rhino?

00:30.117 --> 00:32.554
Elephino.

00:32.597 --> 00:34.338
[chuckles]

00:34.382 --> 00:36.166
Yeah.

00:36.210 --> 00:38.473
That's my first dad joke.

00:40.518 --> 00:42.738
Did you just kick?

00:43.739 --> 00:46.350
Hi, Luna.

00:46.394 --> 00:47.482
You know...

00:47.525 --> 00:48.831
three months from now,

00:48.874 --> 00:50.485
we get to do this in person.

00:50.528 --> 00:51.660
It's pretty cool.

00:54.837 --> 00:56.795
[whispering] Time for our song.

01:01.148 --> 01:04.368
♪ Your love

01:04.412 --> 01:09.373
♪ Is lifting me higher

01:09.417 --> 01:11.723
♪ Than I've ever

01:11.767 --> 01:15.553
♪ Been lifted before

01:15.597 --> 01:18.165
♪ So keep it up

01:18.208 --> 01:21.342
♪ Quenching my desire

01:21.385 --> 01:25.563
♪ And I'll be at your side
forevermore ♪

01:25.607 --> 01:26.782
Jackie Wilson:
♪ You know your love

01:26.825 --> 01:28.131
- How can I help?

01:28.175 --> 01:29.132
- Uh, well, there's
candy machines

01:29.176 --> 01:30.568
in the pediatric ward.

01:30.612 --> 01:32.396
You know what's not good
for kids before 9:00 a.m.?

01:32.440 --> 01:34.572
- Does it start with C and end
with childhood obesity?

01:34.616 --> 01:36.357
- Yes.
- Consider them gone.

01:36.400 --> 01:39.447
[speaking Spanish]

01:50.153 --> 01:51.676
I'm hiring six new therapists

01:51.720 --> 01:53.896
with training in CBT and DBT.

01:53.939 --> 01:55.811
And I'm starting
a patient advocacy division

01:55.854 --> 01:58.770
because when I say things
like CBT and DBT,

01:58.814 --> 02:01.251
patients have no idea
what I'm talking about.

02:01.295 --> 02:02.687
Will this cost more money?

02:02.731 --> 02:04.776
Yes, but...

02:04.820 --> 02:06.343
who's with me?

02:08.215 --> 02:09.825
[elevator bell dings]

02:09.868 --> 02:11.827
- Ooh, uh, we need to talk
about my waiting room.

02:11.870 --> 02:13.307
- Thought we got rid
of your waiting room.

02:13.350 --> 02:14.569
- Well, the plan
was for nurses

02:14.612 --> 02:15.918
to move patients
straight to beds.

02:15.961 --> 02:17.311
- Okay, I'm not seeing
a problem.

02:17.354 --> 02:18.399
- The plan requires nurses.

02:18.442 --> 02:19.748
- Got it.

02:19.791 --> 02:21.619
More nurses.

02:21.663 --> 02:24.666
- ♪ And you know he never
showed his face again ♪

02:24.709 --> 02:27.756
- [speaking Spanish]

02:48.255 --> 02:49.473
- Health care
is the number one cause

02:49.517 --> 02:50.648
of bankruptcy in America.

02:50.692 --> 02:51.823
- Wow, you really know

02:51.867 --> 02:53.347
how to bring things down,
don't you?

02:53.390 --> 02:54.957
- Patients should know
that their...

02:55.000 --> 02:56.959
hospital bills are negotiable.
[breathing heavily]

02:57.002 --> 02:58.874
We should revise our
Patient Bill of Rights.

02:58.917 --> 03:00.223
- Love that idea.

03:00.267 --> 03:01.659
Way to bring things
back up again.

03:01.703 --> 03:02.965
- Okay.

03:03.008 --> 03:05.228
- We need to provide
better care

03:05.272 --> 03:06.490
with fewer resources.

03:06.534 --> 03:09.493
But I need your help.

03:09.537 --> 03:13.454
I need your ideas.

03:13.497 --> 03:14.672
Okay, I'm just gonna do this

03:14.716 --> 03:16.196
until somebody speaks.

03:16.239 --> 03:19.242
Is this jogging anybody's--
Anyone?

03:19.286 --> 03:20.635
I'm gonna go ahead,
it's gonna become a robot now.

03:20.678 --> 03:21.984
It's just gonna go
downhill from here.

03:22.027 --> 03:23.551
I'll just keep on doing this.

03:23.594 --> 03:25.509
Does anybody have anything,

03:25.553 --> 03:27.903
just one idea?

03:27.946 --> 03:29.992
- What about
group appointments?

03:30.035 --> 03:31.428
- Thank God.

03:31.472 --> 03:34.257
Yes. Please, share.

03:34.301 --> 03:36.216
- You give people
with related issues

03:36.259 --> 03:37.956
like diabetes
or high blood pressure

03:38.000 --> 03:39.828
one shared appointment...
- ♪ And I'm so glad

03:39.871 --> 03:42.570
♪ I finally found you

03:42.613 --> 03:46.965
♪ Yes, my one
in a million girl ♪

03:47.009 --> 03:50.534
♪ So I wrap

03:50.578 --> 03:54.364
♪ My loving arms around you

03:57.498 --> 04:01.502
♪ And I can stand up

04:01.545 --> 04:04.983
♪ And face the world

04:05.027 --> 04:06.420
[chuckles softly]

04:09.510 --> 04:10.946
Time to go to work.

04:10.989 --> 04:15.037
[sirens wailing]

04:15.994 --> 04:17.561
- 32-year-old woman collapsed

04:17.605 --> 04:18.910
with extreme
shortness of breath

04:18.954 --> 04:19.911
and chest pain.

04:19.955 --> 04:21.261
Heart rate 140,

04:21.304 --> 04:22.392
respirations 34,

04:22.436 --> 04:23.741
BP 90 over 60.

04:23.785 --> 04:26.309
Took 100% O2 to keep
her sats over 90.

04:26.353 --> 04:27.876
- Where's Reynolds?
Did anyone see what happened?

04:27.919 --> 04:28.877
- I'm her father.

04:28.920 --> 04:30.400
We were at a fund-raiser.

04:30.444 --> 04:32.315
Jozette was
accepting an award.

04:32.359 --> 04:33.925
Then she just shook and fell.

04:33.969 --> 04:35.579
We didn't know what to do.

04:35.623 --> 04:37.059
- What you got?

04:37.102 --> 04:39.322
- Holosystolic blowing murmur
at the apex.

04:39.366 --> 04:40.671
What took you so long?

04:40.715 --> 04:42.064
- Well, I'm the department
chair now.

04:42.107 --> 04:44.284
I've got stuff to do.
- Like what?

04:44.327 --> 04:46.721
- As soon as I figure that out,
I'll let you know.

04:46.764 --> 04:48.810
You're right.
Acute mitral regurgitation.

04:48.853 --> 04:49.811
- Trauma One.

04:49.854 --> 04:50.942
- Get a central line kit.

04:50.986 --> 04:52.770
- Lisa, prepare me
a Levo drip.

04:52.814 --> 04:54.946
- Titrate to systolic at 90.

04:54.990 --> 04:56.774
- On the count of three.

04:56.818 --> 04:58.559
both: One, two, three.

04:58.602 --> 04:59.908
- Watch out.

05:03.041 --> 05:05.609
- Yeah, oh, my gosh,
my girls tested

05:05.653 --> 05:07.742
for their orange belts
last night in karate.

05:07.785 --> 05:09.874
They're complete savages.
I had no idea.

05:09.918 --> 05:11.354
I looked at--I took
a video of it.

05:11.398 --> 05:13.487
Here. I'll show you.

05:13.530 --> 05:15.053
Or wait, did I email it
to myself already?

05:15.097 --> 05:16.533
- That's okay,
I can imagine it.

05:16.577 --> 05:17.839
- Oh, okay.
Well, remind me

05:17.882 --> 05:18.970
to show it to you later,
because it is

05:19.014 --> 05:21.321
intensely cute.
[laughs]

05:21.364 --> 05:22.322
Gosh, I'm always talking
about my kids.

05:22.365 --> 05:23.627
What about you?

05:23.671 --> 05:24.759
How come you never
talk about yours?

05:24.802 --> 05:26.369
- I don't have any.

05:26.413 --> 05:27.936
- Oh, I'm sorry,
I just assumed that you--

05:27.979 --> 05:30.939
- Life had other plans for me,
and then it got too late.

05:30.982 --> 05:32.419
- Okay, well...

05:32.462 --> 05:33.898
speaking of which, based on

05:33.942 --> 05:35.378
your extensive experience...

05:35.422 --> 05:36.988
- You mean to say "old."

05:37.032 --> 05:39.121
- Yes. Exactly.

05:39.164 --> 05:40.818
How long do you think
this Max guy

05:40.862 --> 05:42.951
can shake things up
before the dean steps in?

05:42.994 --> 05:44.909
- Not long.
Dean of medicine does not like

05:44.953 --> 05:46.389
things shaken up...

05:46.433 --> 05:48.435
based on my
extensive experience.

05:48.478 --> 05:49.871
- All right.

05:54.484 --> 05:56.399
Leo. Hi.

05:56.443 --> 05:58.401
How you doing?
I'm Dr. Frome.

05:58.445 --> 05:59.663
But, uh,

05:59.707 --> 06:01.012
you can call me Iggy,
all right?

06:01.056 --> 06:03.885
No need to be so formal.

06:05.887 --> 06:07.671
All right, so...

06:07.715 --> 06:09.499
I had a chat with your mom,

06:09.543 --> 06:10.631
and she told me that
you're having a hard time

06:10.674 --> 06:12.023
staying awake

06:12.067 --> 06:13.721
and that, uh, you've been
wetting the bed.

06:13.764 --> 06:15.549
Is that right?

06:15.592 --> 06:17.420
Okay.

06:17.464 --> 06:19.422
No big deal,
you know?

06:19.466 --> 06:21.468
We can get to the bottom
of this, easy-peasy.

06:21.511 --> 06:23.861
Okay?

06:23.905 --> 06:27.735
[soft music]

06:27.778 --> 06:29.127
Let's see what
we're looking at here.

06:29.171 --> 06:31.434
All right,
says here you've been on...

06:31.478 --> 06:34.916
zotepine for the last
few years?

06:34.959 --> 06:36.047
Is that right?

06:36.091 --> 06:37.919
- Uh-huh.

06:37.962 --> 06:40.922
- Did, uh, something
happen at school?

06:40.965 --> 06:42.489
No? You sure about that?

06:42.532 --> 06:44.926
'Cause zotepine, my friend,
that is...

06:44.969 --> 06:45.927
that's big-time.

06:45.970 --> 06:48.538
That is no joke.

06:48.582 --> 06:50.758
Nothing happened that
you want to tell me about?

06:50.801 --> 06:52.586
- No.

06:52.629 --> 06:54.762
- Okay, cool.
Fair enough.

06:54.805 --> 06:56.851
All right.
They've also got you on...

06:56.894 --> 06:58.853
sertraline.

06:58.896 --> 07:01.725
Huh.

07:01.769 --> 07:03.205
Jeez.

07:03.248 --> 07:06.817
And zolpidem.

07:06.861 --> 07:10.038
Oh, my gosh, they have you
on atomoxetine as well.

07:11.126 --> 07:13.215
Okay. I mean, uh...

07:13.258 --> 07:15.783
who needs breakfast,
am I right?

07:15.826 --> 07:17.567
Fistful of pills like that
every morning?

07:17.611 --> 07:19.134
[gobbles]

07:19.700 --> 07:23.878
♪

07:23.921 --> 07:26.576
Yeah. And I see that, um...

07:26.620 --> 07:28.099
[clears throat] You also...

07:28.143 --> 07:30.798
you lost your dad
a few years back?

07:32.539 --> 07:34.628
Yeah.

07:34.671 --> 07:36.151
Yeah, that's really tough.

07:36.194 --> 07:37.761
I'm sorry.

07:40.721 --> 07:43.811
You know what, Leo?

07:43.854 --> 07:45.943
I want to try
something different.

07:45.987 --> 07:48.685
Instead of adding
more medication

07:48.729 --> 07:51.514
to your already
impressive roster,

07:51.558 --> 07:53.821
why don't we try this
for a plan?

07:53.864 --> 07:55.823
Let's take you off

07:55.866 --> 07:57.172
all of your medication.

08:04.266 --> 08:06.181
- I just want to know how much
this is gonna cost me.

08:06.224 --> 08:07.835
- I'm sorry, but I can't
tell you that.

08:07.878 --> 08:09.532
- So I can compare prices
on my Subaru

08:09.576 --> 08:10.968
and not on my wife's
double bypass?

08:11.012 --> 08:12.840
- You know, it's funny,
Congress actually

08:12.883 --> 08:14.972
made it illegal for hospitals
to disclose prices to you,

08:15.016 --> 08:16.278
so it's the only industry
in America

08:16.321 --> 08:17.801
with a noncompete
clause, but...

08:17.845 --> 08:20.500
call your congressperson.
Resist!

08:21.588 --> 08:22.676
- You're running late.

08:22.719 --> 08:24.068
- For what?
- For everything.

08:24.112 --> 08:25.156
- Dora, I'm educating patients.

08:25.200 --> 08:26.810
- You're inciting riots.

08:26.854 --> 08:27.942
Dean of medicine
called again.

08:27.985 --> 08:29.160
- Pass.

08:29.204 --> 08:30.901
- You can't keep
ignoring him, Max.

08:30.945 --> 08:31.989
When you fire half the staff,

08:32.033 --> 08:33.600
disembowel an entire hospital,

08:33.643 --> 08:35.515
you have to expect your boss
is gonna be on you--

08:35.558 --> 08:38.213
- To what?
Re-bowel it?

08:38.256 --> 08:39.649
Sounds gross, doesn't it?

08:39.693 --> 08:40.998
- Max!

08:41.042 --> 08:42.652
- Dr. Sharpe,
back in the trenches.

08:42.696 --> 08:44.524
How's reentry?
- I wouldn't know.

08:44.567 --> 08:46.003
You didn't show up to your
appointment this morning.

08:46.047 --> 08:47.265
- Well, I had
a department chair meeting.

08:47.309 --> 08:48.876
Which you missed, I believe.

08:48.919 --> 08:50.660
- Because we had
an appointment.

08:50.704 --> 08:51.922
- What--how--did I forget
something?

08:51.966 --> 08:53.141
- No, no, just, uh,

08:53.184 --> 08:54.664
Dr. Sharpe and I
have a little thing.

08:54.708 --> 08:56.057
Very, uh, informal.

08:56.100 --> 08:57.754
- It's not informal.
It's quite serious.

08:57.798 --> 08:59.190
- How serious?
- Not very.

08:59.234 --> 09:00.191
I'm taking care of it.

09:00.235 --> 09:01.192
- Are you?
- Mm-hmm.

09:01.236 --> 09:02.237
- Have you eaten today?

09:02.280 --> 09:03.760
- Does espresso count?

09:03.804 --> 09:05.153
- Dora, would you mind
getting him an apple?

09:05.196 --> 09:06.197
- An apple?
- Mm.

09:06.241 --> 09:07.634
He'll be in my office.

09:07.677 --> 09:08.852
- Uh, can't.
I got a full schedule.

09:08.896 --> 09:10.680
- Your 2:00 p.m.
just canceled.

09:10.724 --> 09:12.116
- Thank you, Dora.

09:12.160 --> 09:13.901
Thought you were
getting me an apple.

09:16.686 --> 09:18.253
- Max.
You have can--

09:18.296 --> 09:19.776
- We have 1,500 patients.

09:19.820 --> 09:21.952
I don't have time
to be one of them.

09:21.996 --> 09:23.563
- You better find the time

09:23.606 --> 09:25.739
before you run out of it.

09:29.743 --> 09:30.134
.

09:30.178 --> 09:32.746
- One of the valves
that controls the flow of blood

09:32.789 --> 09:34.399
through Jozette's heart
is broken,

09:34.443 --> 09:35.531
and blood is backing up
into her lungs,

09:35.575 --> 09:37.359
which is why she can't breathe.

09:37.402 --> 09:40.275
- But how could this happen?
Jozette is strong.

09:40.318 --> 09:42.712
She's an aid worker
for the people of Haiti.

09:42.756 --> 09:44.584
- I have to get to Jean-Rabel.

09:44.627 --> 09:47.238
- This week, a mudslide
hit our village.

09:47.282 --> 09:49.763
So many people have died.

09:49.806 --> 09:51.373
- That might explain
what happened.

09:51.416 --> 09:52.766
- You thinking
takotsubo syndrome?

09:52.809 --> 09:53.767
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

09:53.810 --> 09:54.855
- That sounds bad.

09:54.898 --> 09:56.073
- Another name for it

09:56.117 --> 09:57.640
is, uh, broken heart syndrome.

09:57.684 --> 10:00.295
The mudslide may have caused
Jozette so much grief

10:00.338 --> 10:02.427
that it actually made
her heart beat so hard that

10:02.471 --> 10:04.516
it tore the muscles
that hold it together.

10:04.560 --> 10:06.431
- I hate to feel helpless.

10:06.475 --> 10:07.737
- I'm sorry.
[cell phone buzzes]

10:07.781 --> 10:09.304
- Well, the good news is,

10:09.347 --> 10:11.175
I can fix a broken heart.

10:11.219 --> 10:12.655
Now, we're gonna get you
prepped for surgery

10:12.699 --> 10:14.614
and get you home
as fast as we can.

10:15.919 --> 10:19.227
- First may we perform
a Gad Ko?

10:19.270 --> 10:20.402
- I'm sorry, a what?

10:20.445 --> 10:22.622
- It's a protection ritual.

10:22.665 --> 10:25.450
We make a cut in the skin,
rub in herbs.

10:25.494 --> 10:27.104
- Oh, no, that's out
of the question.

10:27.148 --> 10:29.759
Any cuts to the skin
can introduce infection, so...

10:29.803 --> 10:32.283
- Gad Ko attaches
Lwa to me.

10:32.327 --> 10:34.285
Protects me from accidents.

10:34.329 --> 10:35.678
- Okay, look, Jozette,

10:35.722 --> 10:37.549
there won't be any accidents,
all right?

10:37.593 --> 10:39.160
Now, if you'll excuse me,

10:39.203 --> 10:41.423
I have to prep for surgery.

10:47.908 --> 10:49.257
- It's true.

10:49.300 --> 10:52.652
He used to be energetic.

10:52.695 --> 10:54.175
Silly.
- Yeah.

10:54.218 --> 10:55.742
- But you--you can't just

10:55.785 --> 10:57.874
take him off of all
of his medications.

10:57.918 --> 11:00.181
Doesn't he need them?
- Honestly, I don't know.

11:00.224 --> 11:01.791
I don't know what he needs.
He's on so many

11:01.835 --> 11:04.794
counterintuitive drugs,
I can't see the real issue.

11:04.838 --> 11:06.753
I want to try
behavioral therapy.

11:06.796 --> 11:07.884
Talk therapy.

11:07.928 --> 11:10.887
- He had, um...

11:10.931 --> 11:13.760
outbursts at school--
physical.

11:13.803 --> 11:15.500
And when the school
psychiatrist

11:15.544 --> 11:17.720
started him on the zotepine,
they completely stopped.

11:17.764 --> 11:20.157
- That drug may have succeeded
in curbing your son's behavior,

11:20.201 --> 11:22.594
but it did nothing to address
the underlying issues.

11:22.638 --> 11:25.641
- Zotepine also causes
lethargy, apathy.

11:25.685 --> 11:27.338
So when he was
prescribed a stimulant,

11:27.382 --> 11:28.775
that led to his sleep issues.

11:28.818 --> 11:30.341
- And accelerated
his weight gain,

11:30.385 --> 11:32.387
which developed into
Type 2 diabetes.

11:32.430 --> 11:33.562
- That's why he's
wetting the bed.

11:33.605 --> 11:34.955
He has diabetes...

11:34.998 --> 11:38.393
because of the drugs
that he's on.

11:38.436 --> 11:39.655
- My God, I didn't...

11:39.699 --> 11:40.874
I didn't know.

11:40.917 --> 11:42.614
I mean, they told me
that he needed them.

11:42.658 --> 11:43.964
I was just--I was trying
to help him.

11:44.007 --> 11:45.487
- Of course you were.

11:45.530 --> 11:46.488
That's what we all
would have done.

11:46.531 --> 11:47.707
- Yes, absolutely.

11:47.750 --> 11:49.883
I'm sorry, I just...
[clears throat]

11:49.926 --> 11:52.712
Let me pull him off the meds.

11:52.755 --> 11:53.887
You know, let me talk to him.

11:53.930 --> 11:55.889
I really just want
to talk to him.

12:00.545 --> 12:02.896
When was the last time
you saw your son smile?

12:09.729 --> 12:11.556
- Dora, are you stalking me?

12:11.600 --> 12:14.255
- It's definitely beginning
to feel that way, isn't it?

12:14.298 --> 12:15.299
Dr. Sharpe's office called.

12:15.343 --> 12:16.344
- I got pulled into OB.

12:16.387 --> 12:17.388
- Tell that to Dr. Sharpe.

12:17.432 --> 12:18.955
I got you an apple.

12:18.999 --> 12:20.827
- You know, I'm really more
of a Golden Russet kind of guy.

12:20.870 --> 12:22.350
- Maybe keep that to yourself.

12:22.393 --> 12:23.655
- What do you have against
Golden Russets?

12:23.699 --> 12:24.831
- Nothing, my issue
is with people

12:24.874 --> 12:26.006
who can identify
Golden Russets.

12:26.049 --> 12:27.616
- Dr. Reynolds.
- What up?

12:27.659 --> 12:29.270
- Now eat the apple.
- Got you an apple.

12:29.313 --> 12:31.446
Uh, also, I got a call from
Jozette Pampil's family?

12:31.489 --> 12:32.708
Apparently they're upset
that you won't let them

12:32.752 --> 12:34.754
perform some kind of
protection ritual?

12:34.797 --> 12:36.320
- That's correct.
- Even though they believe

12:36.364 --> 12:38.758
it's gonna help keep
your patient safe from harm?

12:38.801 --> 12:40.803
- You fired the entire
cardiac surgical department

12:40.847 --> 12:42.544
because of the high
infection rates,

12:42.587 --> 12:44.546
and now you want me to let
a family member

12:44.589 --> 12:46.853
cut open my patient
and put dirt in her wound?

12:46.896 --> 12:48.811
- Well, a superficial wound
with a sterile blade

12:48.855 --> 12:51.422
under your supervision.

12:51.466 --> 12:54.338
- Is this my call,
or are you overstepping me?

12:54.382 --> 12:55.862
- It's your call.
- Good.

12:55.905 --> 12:59.300
Then no one's cutting open
my patient but me, okay?

13:00.692 --> 13:02.259
Hello.
- She's ready to go.

13:02.303 --> 13:03.957
- All right. Wow.

13:04.000 --> 13:06.698
Expeditions to the North Pole
traveled lighter, huh?

13:09.963 --> 13:13.488
[alarms beeping]

13:13.531 --> 13:15.664
- Looks like V-fib.

13:15.707 --> 13:18.362
- There's no pulse.
- Defibrillator.

13:18.406 --> 13:19.929
- 200 joules.

13:23.977 --> 13:25.717
- All clear.

13:25.761 --> 13:27.632
[machine jolts]

13:27.676 --> 13:31.071
[alarms continue beeping]

13:31.114 --> 13:32.942
[monitor beeping steadily]

13:32.986 --> 13:34.335
Okay, got her back.

13:34.378 --> 13:35.815
- I'll back off the Levophed.

13:35.858 --> 13:37.077
That should stabilize her.

13:37.120 --> 13:39.601
- You're good?
- Yeah.

13:41.429 --> 13:42.822
Whew.

13:45.346 --> 13:46.521
[alarms beeping]

13:46.564 --> 13:47.870
- Back in V-fib!

13:50.525 --> 13:52.875
- I don't have a pulse.
- Let's go 300.

13:52.919 --> 13:55.530
[alarms continue beeping]

13:55.573 --> 13:57.967
- All clear.

13:58.011 --> 13:59.839
[machine jolts]

13:59.882 --> 14:02.493
[alarms continue beeping]

14:02.537 --> 14:04.844
Okay, I got her back.

14:04.887 --> 14:05.888
What the hell?

14:05.932 --> 14:08.891
[monitor beeping steadily]

14:08.935 --> 14:12.025
- She's too unstable
for transport.

14:12.068 --> 14:15.071
- Maybe you should
do the ritual.

14:18.379 --> 14:20.598
- Because Leo is on
multiple medications,

14:20.642 --> 14:21.948
we must devise a regimented
detox program.

14:21.991 --> 14:23.688
- Mm-hmm.

14:23.732 --> 14:24.864
- The stimulant should leave
his system overnight,

14:24.907 --> 14:26.822
but the psychoactive
medication

14:26.866 --> 14:29.433
will require
gradual tapering.

14:29.477 --> 14:30.695
What, you don't agree?

14:30.739 --> 14:32.697
- No, no, I do. I do.

14:32.741 --> 14:34.917
Just, um, for whatever
it's worth,

14:34.961 --> 14:36.397
I think you would have made
a really good dad.

14:36.440 --> 14:37.702
- No, I wouldn't have.

14:37.746 --> 14:39.356
- Why do you say
these crazy things?

14:39.400 --> 14:40.967
- A word, you two?
- Let me ask you something.

14:41.010 --> 14:42.011
Don't you think Kapoor
would have made,

14:42.055 --> 14:43.839
like, a totally rad dad?

14:43.883 --> 14:46.146
- Uh, Dr. Villarreal, this is--
- Look at this dad face.

14:46.189 --> 14:48.844
- This--hey!
This is Dr. Kapoor,

14:48.888 --> 14:50.628
head of our
neurology department,

14:50.672 --> 14:52.456
and this is Dr. Frome,
head of our psych department.

14:52.500 --> 14:54.110
Gentlemen, this is
Dr. Villarreal.

14:54.154 --> 14:57.026
She's the psychiatrist for all
the public schools in Queens.

14:57.070 --> 14:58.941
- Including Leo Chen's.

14:58.985 --> 15:00.900
His mother alerted me
to the changes

15:00.943 --> 15:02.553
you're making to his treatment.

15:02.597 --> 15:04.991
- Yes, we were just discussing
his detox schedule.

15:05.034 --> 15:06.906
- Well, you should know
that if Leo Chen

15:06.949 --> 15:08.777
stops taking his medication,

15:08.820 --> 15:11.606
he'll no longer be admitted
back into his school

15:11.649 --> 15:14.174
or, for that matter,
any New York public school.

15:14.217 --> 15:15.958
- I'm sorry,
how can you force a child

15:16.002 --> 15:17.090
to take medication?

15:17.133 --> 15:18.918
- Easy, it's the law.

15:21.050 --> 15:23.009
- Prohibition on Mandatory
Medication Amendment.

15:23.052 --> 15:24.924
It passed in 2004.

15:24.967 --> 15:26.621
It is illegal
for public schools

15:26.664 --> 15:28.101
to force a student to take
a controlled substance

15:28.144 --> 15:29.145
to attend class.

15:29.189 --> 15:30.625
- Unless the mother signed

15:30.668 --> 15:32.061
an Individualized
Education Plan

15:32.105 --> 15:33.541
agreeing to the medication.

15:33.584 --> 15:34.803
- She did?
- It's right there.

15:34.846 --> 15:36.544
- Not only are
these medications

15:36.587 --> 15:37.893
causing Leo physical harm,
but nobody has studied

15:37.937 --> 15:39.677
their long-term
side effects, also.

15:39.721 --> 15:41.897
- Well, the school board
doesn't seem to agree with you.

15:41.941 --> 15:43.638
- Max, I can get through
to this kid, just not

15:43.681 --> 15:45.727
with all the drugs in the way.
- Okay, okay.

15:45.770 --> 15:47.468
You really feel
that you can help this kid?

15:47.511 --> 15:49.078
- I do.
- And you think you can

15:49.122 --> 15:51.863
wean him off the drugs safely?
- He does.

15:51.907 --> 15:53.735
What? You gotta talk faster.
- I do.

15:53.778 --> 15:55.867
- Then present your evidence
to a judge.

15:55.911 --> 15:57.043
If you believe this is
the best thing

15:57.086 --> 15:58.783
for your patient,
prove it.

15:58.827 --> 16:00.960
Take the New York
public school system to court.

16:05.747 --> 16:07.488
- This pacing wire
should get her stable

16:07.531 --> 16:08.968
long enough to get her
to the OR.

16:09.011 --> 16:11.100
- Or you could do the ritual.

16:11.144 --> 16:13.624
- If I believed in rituals,
I would have become a shaman,

16:13.668 --> 16:15.713
not a surgeon.

16:15.757 --> 16:17.628
- You're about to fix
her heart valve.

16:17.672 --> 16:19.195
If I were you, I'd take
all the help I could get.

16:19.239 --> 16:20.196
- You know,

16:20.240 --> 16:21.719
if a patient feels like

16:21.763 --> 16:24.200
they've got to chant
or knock on wood

16:24.244 --> 16:27.638
or get their prayer warrior
to lay hands on them

16:27.682 --> 16:28.988
before I operate,
then that means

16:29.031 --> 16:30.641
they don't trust me,
you know?

16:30.685 --> 16:32.034
They don't have faith
in my abilities.

16:32.078 --> 16:35.646
[monitors beeping steadily]

16:35.690 --> 16:37.213
- Normal paced rhythm
with capture.

16:37.257 --> 16:40.173
- See? Pacing wire
is all the faith I need.

16:42.697 --> 16:44.655
[alarms beeping]

16:44.699 --> 16:49.095
- [gasps]
- O2 sats are falling!

16:49.138 --> 16:51.010
- Jozette, I'm gonna sit you up
so you can breathe.

16:51.053 --> 16:54.665
- [gasping]

16:54.709 --> 16:55.840
I hear rales.

16:55.884 --> 16:57.755
- Edema?
- Backing up in her lungs

16:57.799 --> 16:59.496
because of that valve.

16:59.540 --> 17:01.933
Here, toss me the furosemide.
- I'm already on it.

17:01.977 --> 17:04.588
[alarms continue beeping]

17:04.632 --> 17:06.155
You know, that's gonna take
a while to dry out her lungs.

17:06.199 --> 17:08.201
- Well, I can't operate

17:08.244 --> 17:10.029
until I get this under control.

17:10.072 --> 17:11.552
- So then maybe you do
the ritual.

17:11.595 --> 17:14.163
- Don't.

17:14.207 --> 17:15.991
Don't even say it.

17:16.035 --> 17:18.559
[monitor beeping steadily]

17:18.602 --> 17:20.039
- Okay, look, uh,

17:20.082 --> 17:21.823
the ritual isn't even
about you

17:21.866 --> 17:23.042
or what you believe

17:23.085 --> 17:24.086
or your abilities.

17:24.130 --> 17:25.174
It's about her.

17:25.218 --> 17:26.219
It's about what she believes,

17:26.262 --> 17:27.220
what she needs.

17:27.263 --> 17:28.699
I mean...

17:28.743 --> 17:30.788
why can't you just
give her that?

17:33.922 --> 17:35.097
- So, Millie,

17:35.141 --> 17:36.185
I've read your file.

17:36.229 --> 17:38.144
- [chuckles]
Not so good, huh?

17:38.187 --> 17:40.711
- Well, your chemotherapy
hasn't been as effective

17:40.755 --> 17:43.018
as everyone hoped.

17:43.062 --> 17:44.628
Starting tomorrow,
I'd like to put you

17:44.672 --> 17:45.803
on a different regimen.

17:45.847 --> 17:47.849
- [sighs]

17:49.590 --> 17:51.200
- I wish I could offer
better news.

17:51.244 --> 17:53.289
- [sighing] No.

17:53.333 --> 17:55.726
It's okay.

17:55.770 --> 17:59.556
Well, at least
I got to meet you.

17:59.600 --> 18:00.818
- Sorry?

18:00.862 --> 18:02.211
- I've seen you on TV.

18:02.255 --> 18:03.734
- Oh.

18:03.778 --> 18:05.127
- If I had known
I was gonna meet

18:05.171 --> 18:06.563
the real Dr. Helen today,

18:06.607 --> 18:08.348
I would have done my nails.
[chuckles]

18:08.391 --> 18:10.828
- Your nails look fine, Millie.

18:14.136 --> 18:16.878
- No.

18:16.921 --> 18:20.316
None of me looks fine.

18:20.360 --> 18:24.929
[snorts]
I look like a cue ball.

18:24.973 --> 18:30.021
Like a little, shrunken,
nubby-nailed cue ball.

18:30.065 --> 18:31.893
Hell, I tried to wear a wig.

18:31.936 --> 18:33.982
It just kept falling off.

18:34.025 --> 18:35.636
That was...

18:35.679 --> 18:37.768
embarrassing.

18:37.812 --> 18:40.206
Even my kids made fun of me--
which I let them,

18:40.249 --> 18:42.164
because it blows off
steam, and...

18:42.208 --> 18:44.384
I figured if...

18:44.427 --> 18:45.950
they were laughing,

18:45.994 --> 18:47.648
they wouldn't be
thinking about me

18:47.691 --> 18:49.302
keeling over dead.

18:49.345 --> 18:51.042
I just wish

18:51.086 --> 18:53.175
everything didn't
make me nauseous.

18:53.219 --> 18:56.004
Food makes me nauseous.
[speech fading and echoing]

18:56.047 --> 18:59.312
At first, I thought, "Well,
I just won't eat anything,

18:59.355 --> 19:02.228
so what could I throw up?"
[heartbeat thumping]

19:02.271 --> 19:03.925
I was wrong.
- I'm sorry.

19:03.968 --> 19:05.927
Will you ex-excuse me?
I need a moment.

19:05.970 --> 19:08.930
[somber music]

19:08.973 --> 19:14.283
♪

19:14.327 --> 19:15.806
- You okay, Dr. Helen?

19:15.850 --> 19:17.199
- Yep, I just need, um--

19:17.243 --> 19:19.158
I just need my diary.

19:23.423 --> 19:25.251
[sighs]

19:28.210 --> 19:28.428
.

19:28.471 --> 19:30.343
[siren wailing]

19:30.386 --> 19:32.954
- Please tell me
you're joking.

19:34.695 --> 19:36.175
Green Jell-O?

19:36.218 --> 19:37.350
- Well, yeah, but...

19:37.393 --> 19:38.655
we make the food
this bad on purpose

19:38.699 --> 19:40.614
so that nobody wants to stay.

19:40.657 --> 19:42.311
- Well, it's working.
- Yeah.

19:42.355 --> 19:43.443
Tell you what.

19:43.486 --> 19:45.184
I have an apple.

19:46.881 --> 19:48.709
- What about you?
- I'll be all right.

19:48.752 --> 19:50.450
How are you?

19:50.493 --> 19:51.842
- Don't you have
more important patients to see?

19:51.886 --> 19:54.671
- Nope.
- Max. Go.

19:56.369 --> 19:57.544
- Look, I just wanted
to tell you

19:57.587 --> 19:59.633
that I'm not the same...

19:59.676 --> 20:00.677
as that last job.

20:00.721 --> 20:02.723
I can be here...

20:02.766 --> 20:04.420
for you,
with you.

20:04.464 --> 20:06.509
- Max.

20:06.553 --> 20:08.685
It's not just...

20:08.729 --> 20:11.514
Look, even when you
were there, you weren't.

20:11.558 --> 20:12.994
[cell phone buzzes]

20:13.037 --> 20:14.343
- I, um...

20:14.387 --> 20:15.866
[cell phone buzzes]

20:15.910 --> 20:17.216
Sorry, I have to--

20:17.259 --> 20:18.739
- Go.

20:18.782 --> 20:19.957
- [sighs]

20:20.001 --> 20:22.308
- But when you come back,

20:22.351 --> 20:24.614
let me in.

20:27.400 --> 20:28.618
- Promise.

20:28.662 --> 20:30.011
- Thank you for doing this.

20:30.054 --> 20:31.404
I had no idea this was
even possible.

20:31.447 --> 20:32.883
- Yeah, yeah.
You know what?

20:32.927 --> 20:34.363
New Amsterdam was actually
the first hospital

20:34.407 --> 20:36.278
to put a courtroom
in the building

20:36.322 --> 20:39.281
so we could, um, advocate for
our patients in real time,

20:39.325 --> 20:40.761
which is pretty neat.

20:40.804 --> 20:42.328
Leo, come on through here.

20:42.371 --> 20:44.504
You know, in the, uh, 1940s,

20:44.547 --> 20:46.680
uh, New York was having a bit
of a mental health moment,

20:46.723 --> 20:48.377
if you will, and, um,

20:48.421 --> 20:50.292
this psych department
was completely overworked

20:50.336 --> 20:51.989
and underfunded and...

20:52.033 --> 20:53.948
uh, exactly like it is today,

20:53.991 --> 20:55.036
come to think of it.

20:55.079 --> 20:56.037
- [clears throat]

20:56.080 --> 20:57.256
- Oh, right, sorry.

20:57.299 --> 20:58.822
Time to shut up now.

20:58.866 --> 21:01.608
- Mr. Bishop, as Dr. Frome
already knows,

21:01.651 --> 21:04.001
I like to keep
my court informal,

21:04.045 --> 21:05.655
so we're just going to jump in

21:05.699 --> 21:06.961
unless you have any objections.

21:07.004 --> 21:08.484
- None, Your Honor.

21:08.528 --> 21:10.834
- Dr. Kapoor,
we'll start with you.

21:10.878 --> 21:12.401
I've read the file.

21:12.445 --> 21:13.924
You have a course of treatment

21:13.968 --> 21:15.361
you want me to rule on.

21:15.404 --> 21:16.666
I get that.

21:16.710 --> 21:18.538
Tell me why
all this is necessary.

21:19.974 --> 21:22.411
- Good morning, Your Honor.

21:22.455 --> 21:24.326
Leo Chen is only ten years old,

21:24.370 --> 21:25.980
and he's on four different
medications,

21:26.023 --> 21:27.938
many with very damaging
side effects.

21:27.982 --> 21:29.897
But none of the medications
are actually

21:29.940 --> 21:31.768
treating his root problem.

21:31.812 --> 21:32.900
- Which is what?

21:32.943 --> 21:34.554
- Uh, we don't know.

21:34.597 --> 21:36.947
I mean...

21:36.991 --> 21:38.514
we won't until Dr. Frome

21:38.558 --> 21:40.560
can provide the therapy
Leo needs.

21:40.603 --> 21:41.865
- And you don't think
that's possible

21:41.909 --> 21:42.953
while he's medicated?

21:42.997 --> 21:44.651
- Overmedicated.

21:44.694 --> 21:46.783
I don't envy
Dr. Villarreal's position.

21:46.827 --> 21:49.351
She's responsible
for the mental health

21:49.395 --> 21:51.745
of more than 3,000 students.

21:51.788 --> 21:53.486
Prescribing medication
is faster

21:53.529 --> 21:54.965
than painstakingly evaluating

21:55.009 --> 21:57.968
each individual
student's needs.

21:58.012 --> 22:00.841
- That's quite an indictment.
- It's not meant to be.

22:00.884 --> 22:03.409
It's simply the reality
of the situation.

22:03.452 --> 22:05.585
There are too many children
in the public school system

22:05.628 --> 22:07.456
in need of psychological help

22:07.500 --> 22:09.893
and not enough mental health
professionals to help them.

22:09.937 --> 22:13.984
- But you think you
and Dr. Frome can.

22:14.028 --> 22:15.812
- Yes.

22:15.856 --> 22:17.597
In a way that won't
further endanger

22:17.640 --> 22:19.990
Leo's physical health.

22:20.034 --> 22:21.775
We shouldn't have
to choose between

22:21.818 --> 22:23.820
the physical and mental
well-being of our children.

22:27.520 --> 22:29.043
Thank you.

22:30.740 --> 22:34.701
- [singing in Creole]

22:34.744 --> 22:37.747
[shakers rattling,
bells ringing]

22:37.791 --> 22:40.097
[monitors beeping steadily]

22:40.141 --> 22:44.537
[women singing]

22:49.933 --> 22:52.893
[solemn music]

22:52.936 --> 22:59.987
♪

23:17.657 --> 23:24.533
♪

23:24.577 --> 23:27.754
[shakers rattling]

23:27.797 --> 23:34.761
♪

23:34.804 --> 23:38.025
[women chanting]

23:38.068 --> 23:41.463
[shakers rattling]

23:44.684 --> 23:45.859
- All right.

23:45.902 --> 23:46.947
Let's get her to the OR.

23:49.645 --> 23:52.605
[soft music]

23:52.648 --> 23:56.739
♪

23:56.783 --> 23:59.002
Let's go slow.

23:59.046 --> 24:02.005
[monitors beeping steadily]

24:02.049 --> 24:07.141
♪

24:07.184 --> 24:09.970
[sighs]

24:11.798 --> 24:16.672
♪

24:16.716 --> 24:17.978
- The ritual worked.

24:18.021 --> 24:19.806
- Just don't tell Bloom.

24:19.849 --> 24:26.813
♪

24:26.856 --> 24:28.162
- Hey, how's it going?

24:28.205 --> 24:29.685
- Oh, my gosh, so good.

24:29.729 --> 24:30.947
Kapoor nailed it, man.

24:30.991 --> 24:32.732
He was like a slow, bald
ninja out there.

24:32.775 --> 24:33.776
- Nice.

24:33.820 --> 24:35.038
- Ready, Your Honor.

24:35.082 --> 24:37.954
- Okay, let's start with...

24:37.998 --> 24:39.782
the treatment plan

24:39.826 --> 24:42.219
Dr. Kapoor lays out
in Leo's file

24:42.263 --> 24:44.787
seems very reasonable.
What's wrong with it?

24:44.831 --> 24:46.572
- I'm sure it sounds
reasonable, Your Honor,

24:46.615 --> 24:47.616
on paper.

24:47.660 --> 24:48.922
But I'm sorry,

24:48.965 --> 24:51.185
if Leo Chen is taken off
his medications,

24:51.228 --> 24:53.622
he poses a significant threat

24:53.666 --> 24:55.189
to the rest
of the student population.

24:55.232 --> 24:56.625
- That's an exaggeration.

24:56.669 --> 24:58.148
- If I may, Your Honor,

24:58.192 --> 24:59.802
this is video footage
of an incident

24:59.846 --> 25:01.804
at school prior
to Dr. Villarreal

25:01.848 --> 25:04.633
prescribing the medications
in question.

25:05.591 --> 25:06.592
- [clears throat]

25:06.635 --> 25:09.595
[indistinct chatter]

25:09.638 --> 25:12.598
[solemn music]

25:12.641 --> 25:14.904
♪

25:14.948 --> 25:17.864
[blow lands,
students screaming]

25:17.907 --> 25:20.301
[students yelling]

25:20.344 --> 25:22.999
♪

25:23.043 --> 25:26.742
[students shouting, jeering]

25:26.786 --> 25:30.790
[students screaming]

25:30.833 --> 25:36.883
♪

25:36.926 --> 25:39.625
- You're right about
one thing, Dr. Kapoor.

25:39.668 --> 25:42.976
I am responsible
for over 3,000 children,

25:43.019 --> 25:44.586
and I have to protect

25:44.630 --> 25:47.720
the physical well-being
of them all.

25:58.469 --> 25:58.644
.

25:58.687 --> 26:00.384
- Hey.

26:00.428 --> 26:01.690
- They told me
there was a fight.

26:01.734 --> 26:03.431
But I have

26:03.474 --> 26:06.347
never seen
that video before,

26:06.390 --> 26:07.827
and I just--I don't...

26:07.870 --> 26:09.698
- I know.
It's okay.

26:09.742 --> 26:11.613
I know this looks bad.

26:11.657 --> 26:13.572
- I'm not sure "bad" is
the right word to describe it.

26:13.615 --> 26:15.225
- But what we saw on that tape

26:15.269 --> 26:16.618
was rage.

26:16.662 --> 26:18.620
Okay, and there's usually
a reason for rage.

26:18.664 --> 26:20.666
It's, uh--it's situational.
It's not chemical.

26:20.709 --> 26:22.406
- How will you prove that?

26:22.450 --> 26:24.800
- Well...

26:24.844 --> 26:26.802
just give me a second, okay?

26:26.846 --> 26:28.587
I'll be right back.

26:31.328 --> 26:32.634
So listen, Leo.

26:32.678 --> 26:34.549
Do you think maybe
you could tell the judge

26:34.593 --> 26:36.682
what you felt that day?

26:36.725 --> 26:38.292
You know what I mean?

26:38.335 --> 26:40.337
You can tell her
why you did what you did...

26:40.381 --> 26:41.600
in your own words.

26:49.695 --> 26:50.696
Okay.

26:50.739 --> 26:52.349
He can't.

26:52.393 --> 26:54.264
Not on all these meds.
There's no way.

26:54.308 --> 26:55.788
There's just--there's no way.

26:55.831 --> 26:57.746
- There may be one.

27:00.140 --> 27:02.490
- "Thank whatever gods may be

27:02.533 --> 27:04.840
"for my unconquerable soul.

27:04.884 --> 27:08.148
"In the fell clutch
of circumstance...

27:08.191 --> 27:10.498
I have not winced,
nor cried aloud."

27:10.541 --> 27:12.674
- I heard you did the ritual.

27:12.718 --> 27:14.545
I'm glad it helped.

27:16.504 --> 27:18.114
- I'm pretty sure
it was the Levophed,

27:18.158 --> 27:21.378
the pacing wire,
and the furosemide that helped.

27:21.422 --> 27:24.120
- How many times did you,
uh, scrub each finger?

27:24.164 --> 27:26.470
- What?
- How many times?

27:26.514 --> 27:28.342
- Ten.
- Hmm.

27:28.385 --> 27:31.475
Why not 9 or, uh, 11?

27:31.519 --> 27:32.476
Superstition?

27:32.520 --> 27:34.653
- Routine.

27:34.696 --> 27:37.699
- What was that thing
you were reciting earlier?

27:37.743 --> 27:39.266
- "Invictus."

27:39.309 --> 27:41.485
- Oh. Do you always
recite "Invictus"

27:41.529 --> 27:43.662
while scrubbing in?

27:43.705 --> 27:45.489
- I do.

27:45.533 --> 27:46.926
- Kinda like a prayer.

27:46.969 --> 27:48.797
- Mm. Habit.

27:48.841 --> 27:50.625
- Ritual.

27:53.672 --> 27:55.412
Loosen up, Dr. Reynolds.

27:55.456 --> 27:58.198
Not everything's gonna go
according to your plan.

28:05.901 --> 28:08.774
Or everyone.

28:10.863 --> 28:12.386
[machine buzzes]

28:14.736 --> 28:16.477
- Wanna tell me
what's going on?

28:16.520 --> 28:17.783
- Rapid detox dialysis.

28:17.826 --> 28:18.914
- I heard that.
I can see that.

28:18.958 --> 28:20.307
And then I thought,

28:20.350 --> 28:21.525
"Surely they can't be
crazy enough

28:21.569 --> 28:22.744
"to do something like that

28:22.788 --> 28:24.485
in the middle
of court proceedings."

28:24.528 --> 28:25.878
- It's the fastest way
to get psychotropic drugs

28:25.921 --> 28:27.270
out of Leo's system.

28:27.314 --> 28:28.619
- Right, but if we
lose this case,

28:28.663 --> 28:30.578
they are not gonna let Leo
back into school.

28:30.621 --> 28:32.319
- You told us to put
the patient first.

28:32.362 --> 28:33.755
That's what we are doing.
Off these medications,

28:33.799 --> 28:35.365
Iggy will be able
to work with him.

28:35.409 --> 28:37.367
- Yeah, if he can't,
do you have any idea

28:37.411 --> 28:40.675
the kind of liability you are
opening this hospital up to?

28:40.719 --> 28:41.763
- Oh, I see.

28:41.807 --> 28:43.373
- What?

28:43.417 --> 28:44.897
- It's about now
the new medical director

28:44.940 --> 28:47.377
gets his first visit
from the dean of medicine.

28:47.421 --> 28:48.944
Or did the dean already come?

28:48.988 --> 28:49.989
- There you are.

28:50.032 --> 28:51.555
They need you in Hematology,

28:51.599 --> 28:53.340
and you owe Dr. Sharpe a call.

28:53.383 --> 28:54.863
- So patient first
or job first?

29:00.434 --> 29:02.262
- I think we broke him.

29:13.360 --> 29:14.622
- [sighs]

29:14.665 --> 29:16.015
- If you're looking
for a hideout,

29:16.058 --> 29:17.712
this one's taken.

29:19.888 --> 29:21.847
- Who are you running from?

29:21.890 --> 29:24.763
- Patients.

29:24.806 --> 29:26.634
You?

29:26.677 --> 29:28.462
- Doctors.

29:31.639 --> 29:33.510
One in particular.

29:33.554 --> 29:35.643
- [chuckles]

29:37.906 --> 29:39.821
- I shouldn't be here.

29:39.865 --> 29:42.693
- Well, that makes two of us.

29:42.737 --> 29:46.001
I really didn't expect to care

29:46.045 --> 29:48.699
this much.

29:48.743 --> 29:51.311
- That's exactly why
you should be here.

29:55.576 --> 29:58.013
- What about you?

29:58.057 --> 30:01.843
- I made a promise...

30:01.887 --> 30:04.367
to my wife...

30:04.411 --> 30:05.978
that I would slow down.

30:07.718 --> 30:09.808
Before this,
I ran a clinic in Chinatown,

30:09.851 --> 30:10.896
and it almost broke us.

30:10.939 --> 30:14.334
I mean, Georgia...

30:14.377 --> 30:17.641
Georgia couldn't go
through that again.

30:17.685 --> 30:20.079
And I promised that...

30:20.122 --> 30:23.430
she wouldn't have to.

30:23.473 --> 30:26.999
I promised her
that I would be there...

30:29.088 --> 30:31.438
So we could start a family.

30:33.527 --> 30:37.487
So I asked Georgia if
she would slow down with me,

30:37.531 --> 30:38.749
to stop dancing,

30:38.793 --> 30:41.404
a career that she loved,

30:41.448 --> 30:45.017
that she's really,
really good at.

30:47.149 --> 30:49.935
She did...

30:49.978 --> 30:52.981
for me...

30:53.025 --> 30:55.375
to be a mom, you know.

30:58.030 --> 31:00.032
So we got pregnant,
and then

31:00.075 --> 31:02.425
I got the call

31:02.469 --> 31:06.386
about New Amsterdam.

31:06.429 --> 31:09.737
If Chinatown was K2,
then New Amsterdam was...

31:09.780 --> 31:13.610
Everest.

31:13.654 --> 31:16.918
And who can resist
climbing Everest?

31:16.962 --> 31:18.746
- Lots of people.

31:18.789 --> 31:21.792
- I wish I were one of them.

31:21.836 --> 31:25.405
But I said yes...

31:25.448 --> 31:27.886
without telling Georgia.

31:29.583 --> 31:33.021
She didn't like that.

31:33.065 --> 31:35.719
- You betrayed her.

31:35.763 --> 31:38.897
But that doesn't mean
that you don't belong here.

31:38.940 --> 31:40.028
I mean, the changes you've made

31:40.072 --> 31:43.379
are gonna help
thousands of people.

31:43.423 --> 31:47.035
- What about the one
I married?

31:47.079 --> 31:48.732
- Oh, Max.

31:48.776 --> 31:51.605
You haven't told her that you
have cancer, have you?

31:53.476 --> 31:55.826
What are you waiting for?

31:55.870 --> 31:58.568
- To not have cancer?

31:58.612 --> 32:01.658
- You can't carry this load
by yourself--

32:01.702 --> 32:03.965
not as a medical director,
not as a patient,

32:04.009 --> 32:06.968
certainly not as a husband
or father.

32:07.012 --> 32:09.579
You've been telling everyone,
"Put the patient first,"

32:09.623 --> 32:12.104
so why don't you take
your own advice?

32:12.147 --> 32:14.802
Consider this
your first appointment.

32:14.845 --> 32:16.108
And your first order
of business

32:16.151 --> 32:19.850
is to tell your wife
that you have cancer.

32:21.940 --> 32:24.203
- [sighs]

32:29.251 --> 32:29.469
.

32:29.512 --> 32:31.645
- Hey, John,
how am I doing on my suction?

32:31.688 --> 32:33.255
- Good.
- Okay.

32:33.299 --> 32:35.649
Okay, can you give me a 2-0
polyester on a stick?

32:38.521 --> 32:40.393
All right.

32:41.785 --> 32:43.874
There we go.

32:43.918 --> 32:45.441
Snip.

32:45.485 --> 32:46.834
- That should hold nicely.

32:46.877 --> 32:48.183
- That's the goal.

32:48.227 --> 32:49.793
Okay, go ahead
and restore blood flow

32:49.837 --> 32:52.709
from the bypass machine
through the heart.

32:52.753 --> 32:54.537
- Unclamping the aorta...

32:54.581 --> 32:56.713
now.

32:58.585 --> 33:01.022
- Hmm.

33:01.066 --> 33:02.284
Sutures holding.

33:02.328 --> 33:03.720
Blood flow should...

33:03.764 --> 33:05.809
stimulate the heart to start
beating on its own.

33:05.853 --> 33:08.899
- I'm not seeing anything
on monitors.

33:08.943 --> 33:10.989
- Okay, let's give it
a little help.

33:13.295 --> 33:15.428
Okay, here we go.
Charge to 20.

33:16.603 --> 33:19.693
Clear.
[machine jolts]

33:19.736 --> 33:21.738
- No visible beat.

33:21.782 --> 33:24.437
- Let's do it again.

33:24.480 --> 33:25.916
Clear.

33:25.960 --> 33:26.961
[machine jolts]

33:28.963 --> 33:30.225
- Still no heartbeat.

33:30.269 --> 33:31.748
- Gonna need
something stronger.

33:31.792 --> 33:33.489
Intracardiac high-dose EPI.

33:33.533 --> 33:34.925
Give me 10 mls and a syringe.

33:34.969 --> 33:36.971
- Dr. Reynolds.
- I need it now, people.

33:37.015 --> 33:39.974
[suspenseful music]

33:40.018 --> 33:42.890
♪

33:43.804 --> 33:48.330
- Leo, can you tell
Judge Hayashi what you told me?

33:48.374 --> 33:49.766
It's okay.

33:49.810 --> 33:52.030
She's a friend.

33:52.073 --> 33:53.944
- It was my fault.

33:56.817 --> 33:59.037
- What was your fault, Leo?

34:00.864 --> 34:02.823
- My dad died.

34:05.434 --> 34:06.827
My fault.

34:08.872 --> 34:11.919
- Can you tell us the rest?

34:11.962 --> 34:14.052
- We were going
to Sheep's Meadow...

34:14.095 --> 34:16.793
in the park.

34:16.837 --> 34:18.969
That's where we went
to build LEGOs.

34:20.493 --> 34:22.451
- Then what happened?

34:22.495 --> 34:24.584
- Forgot them...

34:24.627 --> 34:28.370
the LEGOs.

34:28.414 --> 34:30.981
So my dad went back
to get them.

34:33.158 --> 34:35.551
And he didn't come back.

34:39.642 --> 34:42.776
- And you live on
a fifth-floor walk-up, right?

34:42.819 --> 34:44.647
Yeah, sometimes it was
hard for his dad

34:44.691 --> 34:46.649
to walk all those stairs.

34:46.693 --> 34:48.651
He had asthma and a...

34:48.695 --> 34:49.913
heart condition.

34:49.957 --> 34:52.568
And that day when he
reached the top,

34:52.612 --> 34:54.483
he had a heart attack.

34:54.527 --> 34:56.398
And Leo found him.

34:59.793 --> 35:02.361
- And the video?

35:02.404 --> 35:05.451
Can you tell me what happened?

35:05.494 --> 35:08.454
- Ryder...

35:08.497 --> 35:10.064
he always said
I should be dead

35:10.108 --> 35:12.762
like my dad.

35:12.806 --> 35:14.590
That day,

35:14.634 --> 35:16.636
I finally...

35:16.679 --> 35:18.681
I had to make it stop.

35:22.555 --> 35:25.035
- [sighs]

35:25.079 --> 35:27.777
What are you proposing,
Dr. Frome?

35:27.821 --> 35:28.996
- Well...
[clears throat]

35:29.039 --> 35:30.650
Leo needs to be able to process

35:30.693 --> 35:32.739
all this displaced guilt.

35:32.782 --> 35:34.044
And he can't do that
when he's buried

35:34.088 --> 35:36.003
in a drug-induced haze.

35:36.046 --> 35:38.353
He needs to be able to feel.

35:38.397 --> 35:39.876
He needs to be able
to talk to somebody.

35:39.920 --> 35:41.574
[clears throat]

35:41.617 --> 35:43.967
Let him talk to me.

35:44.011 --> 35:46.056
Let me help him.

35:51.192 --> 35:52.759
- Charged to 20.
- Clear.

35:52.802 --> 35:55.022
[machine jolts]

35:55.065 --> 35:56.806
All right, paddles in place.
- How long do we keep this up?

35:56.850 --> 35:59.853
- Paddles in place!
Nurse, loupes!

35:59.896 --> 36:01.724
- Charged to 20.
- Clear!

36:01.768 --> 36:04.510
[machine jolts]

36:04.553 --> 36:05.728
- Still nothing.

36:07.774 --> 36:10.385
- Dr. Reynolds.

36:10.429 --> 36:12.561
Do we call it?

36:12.605 --> 36:15.477
[tense music]

36:15.521 --> 36:21.918
♪

36:21.962 --> 36:23.746
What are you doing?

36:23.790 --> 36:26.967
- Trying cardiac massage.

36:27.010 --> 36:28.011
- That's not going to work.

36:28.055 --> 36:30.623
- All I need is one beat.

36:30.666 --> 36:31.754
Just one.

36:31.798 --> 36:33.191
Come on.

36:34.975 --> 36:36.933
- Dr. Reynolds.

36:36.977 --> 36:38.021
Dr. Reynolds.

36:38.065 --> 36:40.459
- Hold on, no.

36:40.502 --> 36:43.113
I think I feel something.

36:43.157 --> 36:45.115
I feel something.

36:45.159 --> 36:47.509
- Are you sure?

36:47.553 --> 36:50.947
[music swells]

36:50.991 --> 36:52.819
[monitor beeping steadily]

36:52.862 --> 36:56.083
[heartbeat thumping]

36:56.126 --> 36:57.737
- She's back.

37:00.827 --> 37:02.785
- You did it.

37:02.829 --> 37:05.440
[heartbeat continues thumping]

37:05.484 --> 37:08.051
[monitor continues beeping]

37:20.716 --> 37:22.675
- So...

37:26.896 --> 37:29.072
The Gad Ko worked.

37:29.116 --> 37:32.598
[soft music]

37:32.641 --> 37:34.077
- [sighs]

37:34.121 --> 37:41.041
♪

37:47.874 --> 37:50.833
[soft acoustic music]

37:50.877 --> 37:57.884
♪

